    - m_Type: 0
      Title:
        m_Untranslated: 
      Text:
        m_Untranslated: As shown in the diagram above, if we know the position and
          velocity of the target, then we can predict where the target will be in
          <c>n</c> seconds from now (or some fraction of a second), by multiplying
          the velocity by <c>n</c> . This assumes that the target will keep the same
          velocity over those n seconds. While this is unlikely, it will still result
          in a more difficult enemy to evade. We will see that adjusting the value
          of <c>n</c> can change the difficulty of the enemy (although it is likely
          you will hit a point of diminishing returns or even worse behaviour if
          you predict too far, as the likelihood of a target maintaining the same
          velocity for an extended period of time is low).
